bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Some of Trump=E2=80=99s henchmen, too, are priv=
ately suspicious of Musk,
whom they view as a quasi-libertarian who=E2=80=99s opportunistically leani=
ng into border issues and race panic to cosplay Trumpian bona fides. =E2=80=
=9CIn his heart, does he really believe those things?=E2=80=9D said one MAG=
A figure. Elon is not =E2=80=9C100 percent fluent in the native tongue of M=
AGA,=E2=80=9D another source said, but he became the movement=E2=80=99s pre=
mium sponsor despite a lack of institutional knowledge. Meanwhile, he=E2=80=
=99s more unpredictable and erratic than Trump himself. =E2=80=9CNobody is =
quite sold on who he actually is,=E2=80=9D the
source added.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Indeed, Musk=E2=80=99s prox=
imity to Trump has alienated certain people charged with operating the next=
 White House. Some have whispered that Musk is dismissive of chief of staff=
 <strong>Susie Wiles</strong>=E2=80=94whom the staff exalts=E2=80=94and tha=
t he parades into meetings unbidden. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s not great to the=
 staff,=E2=80=9D said a source familiar with the situation. =E2=80=9CHe wan=
ders into these meetings=E2=80=94six months
of work and he can throw it out.=E2=80=9D Others close to the president-ele=
ct rejected that characterization as inaccurate, and even, perhaps, an atte=
mpt to drive a wedge between Trump=E2=80=99s allies where none exists.</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">When asked for comment, Trump spokesperson <strong>Steven C=
heung</strong> offered this: =E2=80=9CThese sources are full of shit and ha=
ve no idea what they are talking about. Instead of making up outright lies,
they should focus their time on self-reflection to better understand what h=
appened in their lives that led them down this dark path. It is a well-know=
n fact that Susie has helped President Trump assemble the most competent an=
d experienced team in history to implement the America First agenda the peo=
ple of this country voted for.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Critics presume=
 that familiarity will breed contempt, especially once Musk
moves into an office across the street from Trump=E2=80=99s own. But in str=
ange ways, Musk=E2=80=99s gonzo political style seems to have worked in his=
 favor. The Musk management philosophy=E2=80=94which can be distilled as a =
maniacal focus on microscopic details in the spirit of breaking down an ent=
erprise before building it back up=E2=80=94hasn=E2=80=99t been fully tested=
 in the realm of politics. The person who came closest was probably Trump h=
imself, who saw his first-term agenda hamstrung by his lack of knowledge ab=
out Washington
procedures and mores. Musk, too, is a neophyte in the ways of Washington, a=
nd without allies on the Hill.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Anyway, Musk could=
<em> buy</em> an army of operatives to teach him the ways of Washington=E2=
=80=94he=E2=80=99s already hired <strong>Chris Young</strong> and has been =
working with <strong>Generra</strong> <strong>Peck</strong> and <strong>Phi=
l Cox</strong> on his America PAC. Meanwhile, he has the resources to
fund primary challenges against incumbents who thwart Trump=E2=80=99s agend=
a=E2=80=94<strong>Chris LaCivita</strong> would be a natural ally in this e=
ndeavor=E2=80=94and he has law firms and public affairs shops dying to work=
 for him. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s in such a unique spot=E2=80=94there=E2=80=
=99s no historic parallel, other than a really powerful presidential spouse=
, like a <strong>Nancy Reagan</strong>, whom you had to keep happy,=E2=80=
=9D one K Street veteran told me. =E2=80=9CAt the same time, everyone is li=
ke, <em>How long can this last?</em>=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Tru=
mp has shown there are limits to Musk=E2=80=99s sway=E2=80=94he rejected Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s advocacy of <strong>Howard Lutnick</strong> for treasury secre=
tary in favor of <strong>Scott Bessent</strong>, for instance, and declined=
 to support <strong>Rick Scott</strong> for Senate majority leader. There a=
re also frustrations with Musk on the Hill, where his last-minute intervent=
ion in <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>=E2=80=99s spending bill led the
government to the brink of a shutdown. =E2=80=9CSenators get the joke a lit=
tle bit more,=E2=80=9D said a former Senate aide. =E2=80=9CThey see Musk as=
 a crazy donor. Everyone is being polite, but most people question the long=
evity he has here. There=E2=80=99s too much ego for the whole relationship =
to not blow up.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>And yet, <strong>Sa=
m Nunberg</strong>, the political consultant and Trump 2016 advisor, disagr=
ees with this increasingly popular sentiment that the bromantasy must end. =
=E2=80=9CEverybody keeps
saying that Trump may be getting tired of him, but here=E2=80=99s the thing=
: Elon=E2=80=99s <em>still there</em>,=E2=80=9D Nunberg said. =E2=80=9CHe=
=E2=80=99s the largest donor of all time. He ran his national get-out-the-v=
ote movement. He campaigned in Pennsylvania and targeted young males. He ru=
ns the largest [electric] automotive company, and that=E2=80=99s one of his=
 <em>side projects</em>. He=E2=80=99s not going anywhere.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p=
></div>
